      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insights\n\nThis network beautifully illustrates the **amphoteric** nature of zinc. In acidic solution, Zn²⁺ dominates; as pH rises, successive hydroxo complexes form — Zn(OH)⁺ → Zn(OH)₂(aq) → Zn(OH)₃⁻ → Zn(OH)₄²⁻ (the zincate ion). The network also captures **five crystallographic polymorphs** of solid Zn(OH)₂ plus ZnO, each with slightly different solubility products. The amorphous form (log K = −14.82) is notably more soluble than the crystalline phases (log K ≈ −15.5 to −16.0), consistent with the general principle that amorphous solids have higher free energy and dissolve more readily. This rich speciation is why zinc hydroxide chemistry is central to understanding corrosion, galvanizing, and zinc-air battery electrochemistry.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (SRD-46)*",
        "claims": [
          {
            "start": 0,
            "end": 22,
            "text": "### Chemistry Insights",
